reply.text: It's complicated. The farmers own small patches of land and machines needed to remove the stubble from the ground are very expensive, way beyond what these small farmers can afford. author: SYD - Music
text:
I am originally from Germany and that‚Äôs also where I live. 
But after I graduated school in July, I decided to come to Delhi, India for 4 months and visit my family here. 
I am used to breathe clean fresh village air in Germany. 
After 2 months I realized that my throat was kind of itchy pretty often. 
And it‚Äôs getting worse by every week (in winters). 
I sometimes have problems breathing when I am in gym doing intensive exercises. 
I am here for 3 more weeks before I am going back to Germany. 
All I can say is that people who are on the streets suffer the most. 
At least I can say that I am in a closed house (which also has pollution inside but it‚Äôs much less). 
When going out, I mostly travel with an Uber which means I‚Äôm only facing smog for a little amount of time. But still I can feel the effects of this hazardous air quality. 
Politicians really need to ban these fires as soon as possible so that Indian inhabitants will no longer face such extreme conditions in future.

author: Giang Huynh
text: You cannot simply enforce a law like that without drawing an alternative solution. If the stubble burning is enough to more than quadruple the pollution in the big city, then it means the source of it is so large no amount of law enforcement can effectively stop it. What need to be done it to draw up a plan to work with farmers. Stubbles can be processed in many way to produce fuel, animal feed or soil fertiliser. Moreover, burning stubble will severely damage the soil over time for several reason: the heat removes moisture causing top soil easier to be blow away, the sudden rise in carbon will also alter the pH level (in most case the field is flooded right away which will produce more acid). Therefore without the increased pollution in Dheli, stubble burning is a bad move anyway, and right from the beginning there should have been plan to process them properly like processing factories, government agencies that educate farmers and more equipment investment. This problem can be solved, but not right on the year, the month that the law is passed because it is stemmed from unthoughtful planning on such a large scale.

reply.text: Stubble burning is a bad practice even for an agricultural process not mentioning the pollution factor. It will heavily damage the soil. However, farmers‚Äô malpractice cannot solely be blamed on them, because the soil and water resources belong to all and the government should have made a better plan when they encourage and build such a large farming region. Let‚Äôs face it, the farmers may seen like the main culprits for pollution here, but they are who feed India‚Äôs massive population. The citizens in Dheli can complain about the air all they want but that is what put food in their stomachs. With such a huge population, food security is a big problem and inevitably some consequences will happen. I have worked in agriculture for 5 years and in matters like this it is always hard to judge just one side of the problem. On the one hand the farmers are misusing the resources and actively causing environmental issue, Dheli‚Äôs case is just one of many. But on the other hand farmers are made up of uneducated people, while there isn‚Äôt enough experts and agents with authority to educate and control so many people in so massive geographical settings. The agricultural field is sorely lacking in brain power, and part of that problem stems from society‚Äôs attitudes toward it.

reply.author: Arnimal Kaul
reply.text: Sadly enough the stubble burning problem was created by the government. Punjab and Haryana never grew rice since they don't get heavy enough monsoons. They instead used to grow wheat primarily. But now due to subsidies provided by government towards growing rice as well, they grow a crop which in India's long history was never grown in that area. On top of that there is very short time between the kharif and rabi crop cycles, so there is pressure on these farmers to get rid of the stubble from the previous crop cycle as soon as possible to plant the next crop. The crop cutting used to be done by hand before which would leave minimal stubble back. But now tractors are used which only cut the top parts of the crop where the grain is, leaving behind a much longer stubble.\nIn short the solution is to discourage rice plantation in these states and encourage it in monsoon heavy areas of the country. We anyways have a surplus of grains every year.

India is just going through the same phases they did but later because they are industrialized late. The only difference today is that the 1st world nations gave developing nations newer technology that they didn't adapt to and skipped several steps within the development cycle. You don't just jump from ox and horses to gasoline cars and expect your nation to cope with the consequences. This is not Sid Meier's Civilization. reply.author: SandyRiverBlue
reply.text: Strict emission controls. At first corporations and business owners bucked at these controls, stating that the emissions goals were crippling and that the technology to cap emissions did not exist. Lawmakers let them know in uncertain terms that these regulations would be put in place and that if they wanted to stay in business they would need to rise to meet their obligations. Practically the new regulations were rolled out stepwise, with emissions goals every few years over the course of 12 years or so. The outcome was that the technologies were created in both the manufacturing and automobile fronts to meet these goals. A side effect of these investments in clean technology were huge efficiency gains that paid for themselves many times over and ultimately because California has the largest population in the States, and so have strong purchasing power, this cleantech became cheaper for the rest of the country. California is now one of the largest economies in the world. \nOften doing the best thing for the environment also happens to be the best thing for your bottom line.

reply.author: Lilac Lizard
reply.text:
@Sandeep The best solution is bio-char, let the farmers continue burning, but provide them with large containers to pack the waste into before burning it, so that the carbon is left behind in the burning process. That carbon can then be added to the soils to retain more water & nutrients & therefore increase productivity of the land, while reducing input costs & no extra time for crop waste disposal.


If you want to see how simple it is, fill an old coffee or other tin container with organic waste like paper, punch a small hole in the lid & put onto a fire or cooktop until you can no longer light the gasses escaping from the punched hole & there you go, solid carbon, stable in solid form for 1000 years. That escaping gas can be used to fuel the burning, but all the smog causing carbon particles are being trapped in solid form due to the container depriving them of oxygen, so no more crop burning smog :)

reply.author: Lilac Lizard
reply.text:
Nir Gadish, stop getting into complex & expensive "solutions". If you want to promote carbon capture, do it in an accessible way. It's quite viable for them to carbon capture as bio-char. If that's what you mean, say it outright, if your biofuel is something more complicated than that, then ask yourself why you are overcomplicating things to the point that they will no longer be practical.


All that needs to happen is for farmers to be given a basic bio-char unit (basically a tin can with a small hole in the top & a tube that runs from the hole to below the tin, so that the wood gasses escaping from the tin can fuel the burning to create the bio-char that is solid form, 1000 years stable charcoal) Stop over-engineering!

reply.author: Lilac Lizard
reply.text:
@KaTaRa If the government gives them a bio-char burner, it's practical for them to use it. The bio-char burner uses the materials being burnt as the fuel to operate it & just retains the carbon as a solid. If the carbon is plowed into the cropfields, it will hold 70 times it's weight in water & fertiliser & consequently save the farmers money/increase their yield, while taking barely any additional time to do.


If you want to see it in action, get an old coffee or other metal tin, punch a hole in the top, fill it with paper, leaves or other organic matter & put it on a fire or your cooktop & heat until you cannot ignite the gasses coming out of the hole in the top. That's all there is to making bio-char, very simple & cheap equipment & process. Sad when it gets overcomplicated to the point that people very understandably write it off

reply.author: Dinesh Kumar
reply.text:
@Nilesh Kumar You may be right, farmers don't contribute to our GDP, loans have been waived off. My father has a land and he gives it to people for farming by renting it. Do you know how many times my dad has collected rent from them?
They fail to pay more than half of the time a year.
Do you know why we still rent it out even when the miss the payment? 
We as farmers know how it is like man. Uneven rainfall kills crops, many times the crops the grow is not in demand and thus farmers don't make much. If two years you don't see profit you might see it in the third year. That profit is split and payed out for loan and rent it is and thier expenses. When everting is done they don't have a rupee left. So it loan time again.
What will you do to people who cant pay of their loan and the source of income is unreliable at best?  Do you let them rot? If everybody had the same idea as you to not waiver of loan when in desperation there would be a huge spike in farmer suicides. Once that is done then will you get up from your couch and  phone and start farming?
Do you know how? If you do then good. Even if you do and there is heavy rainfall for a week and crops destroyed will you not ask for help from government? You will.

reply.text:
Sarita Sinha 

exactly

you guys in india have come so far!  you have about the same population as china, but your population is younger and more able to work.  china's one child policy made sure of that.  you've made massive strides in your space program ISRO, and also massive strides in women's empowerment.  but women are still more valued in china than india, which is in large part the reason their economy is doing better.  there's still a lot more work to do.  

pollution is a huge issue too.  india and china are both very possibly the future superpower of asia.  russia is in decline, but india and china are making their way into the first world, and becoming superpowers big enough to rival the usa.

but studies have repeatedly shown that women's empowerment is one of the most discerning factors of a first world country.  when women can enter the work force, earn money, contribute to the economy, control their own reproductive health and have children at an older age, they're more financially stable.  studies repeatedly show that empowered women have fewer children, but are able to spend more resources on those children to turn them into more productive members of society.  pollution control and women's rights are the two biggest issues to tackle before india can become the dominant power in asia.  i'd honestly much rather have india as the main power in asia, instead of china.  every country has its flaws, obviously, but if india can get their act together, you'll definitely be more humanitarian than the dictatorship in china.  i love chinese people, but their government is totalitarian and dangerous, so we should honestly all be worried about them.
